Building Downtown Los Angeles Leland Saito traces these two parallel trends through specific construction projects and the backlash they provoked. He uses these events to theorize the past and present processes of racial formation and the racialization of place, drawing new insights on the relationships between race, place, and policy. Saito brings to bear the importance of historical events on contemporary processes of gentrification and integrates the fluidity of racial categories into his analysis. He explores these forces in action, as buyers and entrepreneurs meet in the real estate marketplace, carrying with them a fraught history of exclusion and vast disparities in wealth among racial groups.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCentral business districtszCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aCity planningzCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aGentrificationzCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aMinoritieszCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aUrban renewalzCaliforniazLos Angeles. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh  aCommunity Benefits Agreements.  aGentrification.  aconvention centers.  agrowth coalitions.  aracial formation.  aracial wealth gap.  aracial-spatial formation.  aracialization of place.  asocial justice coalitions.  asports arenas.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076648640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363253040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503632530423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503632530/original  a978-3-11-076648-6  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles